<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Common Baking Pan Measurements</h2>



<p>In this list, you=E2=80=99ll find common baking pan measurements and the=
 volume of batter they hold. **<strong>The amount listed is the total amoun=
t of batter each pan holds, but you usually only fill cake pans halfway (un=
less otherwise noted in the recipe you are using).</strong>** Most measurem=
ents were taken at my home kitchen. Cross referenced with the always truste=
d <a href=3D"https://www.joyofbaking.com/PanSizes.html" target=3D"_blank" r=
el=3D"noopener">Joy of Baking</a>, as well.</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Measurement Conversions</h3>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><strong>1 inch =3D 2.54cm</strong></li>



<li><strong>1 cup =3D 240ml</strong></li>
</ul>



<p><strong>Round Pans:</strong><br>6=C3=972 inches (15 x 5cm) =3D 4 cups (9=
60ml)<br>8=C3=972 inches (20 x 5cm) =3D 6 cups (1.4 liters)<br>9=C3=972 inc=
hes (23 x 5cm) =3D 8 cups (1.9 liters)</p>



<p><strong>Square Pans:</strong><br>8=C3=972 inch square (20 x 5 cm) =3D 8 =
cups (1.9 liters)<br>9=C3=972 inch square (23 x 5 cm) =3D 10 cups (2.4 lite=
rs)<br>10=C3=972 inch square =3D (25 x 5 cm) =3D 12 cups (2.8 liters)</p>



<p><strong>Rectangular Pans =E2=80=93 </strong><em>2 inch (5 cm) tall</em><=
br>11=C3=977 inches (28 x 18 cm) =3D 10 cups (2.4 liters)<br>13=C3=979 inch=
es (33 x 23 cm) =3D 14 cups (3.3 liters)</p>



<p><strong>Springform Pans:</strong><br>9x 2.5 inches (23 x 6 cm) =3D 10 cu=
ps (2.4 liters)<br>10x 2.5 inches (25 x 6 cm) =3D 12 cups (2.8 liters)</p>



<p><strong>Bundt Pan =E2=80=93</strong> <em>volume varies because of variou=
s designs</em><br>10=C3=973 inch (25 x 8 cm) =3D 10-12 cups (2.8 liters)</p=
>



<p><strong>Tube Pan:</strong><br>9=C3=973 inches (23 x 8 cm) =3D &nbsp;12 c=
ups (2.8 liters)</p>



<p><strong>Jelly Roll Pans =E2=80=93 </strong><em>1 inch (2.5 cm) tall</em>=
<br>10=C3=9715 inches (27 x 39 cm) =3D 10 cups (2.4 liters)<br>12=C3=9717 i=
nches (32 x 44 cm) =3D 12 cups (2.8 liters)</p>



<p><strong>Loaf Pans =E2=80=93</strong><em> about 3 inches (8 cm) tall&nbsp=
;</em><br>8=C3=974 inch (20 x 10 cm) =3D 4 cups (960 ml)<br>9=C3=975&nbsp; =
inch (23 x 13 cm) =3D 8 cups (1.9 liters)</p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading">How to Determine the Volume Yourself</h2>



<p>If you want to calculate a pan=E2=80=99s volume yourself, it=E2=80=99s s=
o easy! Simply fill your pan with 1 cup of water at a time and count until =
it=E2=80=99s full. That=E2=80=99s what I do!</p>



<hr class=3D"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity">



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading">How Much Does This Pan Hold?</h2>



<p>Here=E2=80=99s a helpful list of the most common baking pans and the vol=
ume of batter they hold, as well as which pans hold the same amount of batt=
er. ***<strong>Keep in mind that the volumes listed mean you are filling th=
e pan all the way to the top with batter, which isn=E2=80=99t ideal for bak=
ed goods.</strong> Unless otherwise noted, filling pans around 2/3 full is =
the best practice. This leaves room for rising.</p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>For example, my <a href=3D"https://sallysbakingaddiction.com/vanilla-ca=
ke/" rel=3D"">vanilla cake</a> recipe yields around 8 cups of batter which =
I divide between 3 9=C3=972 inch round cake pans. (Each hold 8 cups of batt=
er!) Each cake layer has a little less than 3 cups batter each.</li>
</ul>



<p>Use the following section to determine which baking pans can be substitu=
ted for others based on their full volume.</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Round Pans</h3>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><strong>6=C3=972 inch round pan holds 4 cups of batter</strong>, the sa=
me as an 8=C3=974 inch loaf pan. Fun discovery! Cupcake recipes yielding 12=
-16 cupcakes fit wonderfully in 3 6-inch cake pans. See my post for <a href=
=3D"https://sallysbakingaddiction.com/6-inch-cake-recipes/" rel=3D"">6 inch=
 cake</a> recipes for more information.</li>



<li><strong>8=C3=972 inch round pan holds 6 cups of batter</strong>.</li>



<li><strong>9=C3=972 inch round pan holds 8 cups of batter</strong>, the sa=
me as an 8=C3=972 inch square pan and a 9=C3=975 inch loaf pan.</li>



<li><strong>10=C3=972 inch round pan holds 10-11 cups of batter</strong>, t=
he same as a 9=C3=972 inch square pan, 11=C3=977 inch pan, 10=C3=9715 inch =
jelly roll pan, 10=C3=973 inch Bundt pan, and a 9=C3=972.5 inch springform =
pan.</li>
</ul>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Square Pans</h3>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><strong>8=C3=972 inch square pan holds 8 cups of batter</strong>, the s=
ame as a 9=C3=972 inch round pan and a 9=C3=975 inch loaf pan.</li>



<li><strong>9=C3=972 inch square pan holds 10 cups of batter,</strong> the =
same as a 10=C3=972 inch round pan, 11=C3=977 inch pan, 9=C3=972.5 inch spr=
ingform pan, 10=C3=973 inch Bundt pan, and a 10=C3=9715 inch jelly roll pan=
.</li>



<li><strong>10=C3=972 inch square pan holds 12 cups of batter,</strong> the=
 same as a 12=C3=9717 inch jelly roll pan, 10=C3=973 inch Bundt pan, 10=C3=
=972.5 inch springform pan, and a 9-inch tube pan.</li>
</ul>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Rectangle Pans</h3>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><strong>11=C3=977 inch pan holds 10 cups of batter,</strong> the same a=
s a 10=C3=972 inch round pan, 9=C3=972-inch square pan, 9=C3=972.5 inch spr=
ingform pan, 10=C3=973 inch Bundt pan, and a 10=C3=9715 inch jelly roll pan=
.</li>



<li><strong>9=C3=9713 inch pan holds 14-16 cups of batter,</strong> essenti=
ally the same as 2 9=C3=972-inch round pans.</li>
</ul>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Jelly Roll Pans</h3>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><strong>10=C3=9715 inch jelly roll pan holds 10 cups of batter,</strong=
> the same as a 10=C3=972 inch round pan, 9-inch square pan, 11=C3=977 pan,=
 9=C3=972.5 inch springform pan, 10-inch Bundt pan.</li>



<li><strong>12=C3=9717 inch jelly roll pan holds 12 cups of batter,</strong=
> the same as a 10=C3=972 inch square pan, 10-inch Bundt pan, 10=C3=972.5 i=
nch springform pan, and a 9-inch tube pan.</li>
</ul>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Bundt Pans</h3>



<p><em>10-inch Bundt pans are the standard size. I actually have several th=
at are 9.5 inches and most Bundt cake recipes still fit.</em></p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><strong>10-inch Bundt pan holds 10-12 cups of batter,</strong> the same=
 as a 10=C3=972 inch round pan (10 cups), 9=C3=972 inch square pan (10 cups=
), 10=C3=972 inch square pan (12 cups), 11=C3=977 inch pan (10 cups), 10=C3=
=9715 inch jelly roll pan (10 cups), 12=C3=9717 inch jelly roll pan (12 cup=
s), 9=C3=972.5 inch springform pan (10 cups), 10=C3=972.5 inch springform p=
an (12 cups) and a 9-inch tube pan (12 cups).</li>
</ul>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Tube Pans</h3>



<p><em>9=C3=973 inch tube pans are the standard size. I have a few that are=
 8 inch and 10 inch and most recipes using tube pans fit nicely in all.</em=
></p>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><strong>9=C3=973 inch tube pan holds 12 cups of batter,</strong> the sa=
me as 10=C3=972 inch square pan, 12=C3=9717 inch jelly roll pan, and a 10=
=C3=972.5 inch springform pan.</li>
</ul>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Springform Pans</h3>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><strong>9=C3=972.5 inch springform pan holds 10 cups of batter,</strong=
> the same as a 10=C3=972 inch round pan, 9=C3=972 inch square pan, 11=C3=
=977 inch pan, a 10=C3=9715 inch jelly roll pan.</li>



<li><strong>10=C3=972.5 inch springform pan holds 12 cups of batter,</stron=
g> the same as a 10=C3=972 inch square pan, 12=C3=9717 inch jelly roll pan,=
 and a 9=C3=973 inch tube pan.</li>
</ul>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Loaf Pans</h3>



<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><strong>8=C3=974 inch loaf pan holds 4 cups of batter,</strong> the sam=
e as a 6=C3=972 inch round pan.</li>



<li><strong>9=C3=975 inch loaf pan holds 8 cups of batter,</strong> the sam=
e as a 9=C3=972 inch round pan and an 8=C3=972 inch square pan.</li>
</ul>



<hr class=3D"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity">



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Substituting Cake Pans</h2>



<p>I=E2=80=99m piggy-backing this one to the section above because there=E2=
=80=99s often a need to substitute different cake pans. If substituting a b=
aking pan that holds the same amount of batter, be wary of the baking time =
because the dimensions of the baked good will change. Always keep your eye =
on the oven and begin checking for doneness earlier than the recipe states.=
</p><div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_2_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad adthrive-con=
tent adthrive-content-2 adthrive-ad-cls" style=3D"min-height: 250px;"></div=
>



<p>Remember, only fill pans about 1/2 to 2/3 full unless otherwise instruct=
ed in the recipe.</p>



<figure class=3D"wp-block-image aligncenter"><img decoding=3D"async" width=
